  "prompt": "Which is a good refrence book for Servlets and JSP?",
  "response": "For learning Servlets and JSP (JavaServer Pages), several references are highly regarded. Here are a few of the most recommended books:\n\n1. **\"Head First Servlets and JSP\" by Bryan Basham, Kathy Sierra, and Elisabeth Robson**  \n   This book uses a unique visual format that makes it engaging and easier to learn. It covers both Servlets and JSP thoroughly, along with practical examples and quizzes to reinforce understanding.\n\n2. **\"Java Servlet & JSP Cookbook\" by Chris Shiflett**  \n   This book provides practical solutions to common problems encountered when working with Servlets and JSP. It's a useful resource for intermediate developers looking for specific use cases and techniques.\n\n3. **\"Beginning Java EE 7\" by Antonio Goncalves**  \n   Although it's more focused on the broader Java EE platform, this book includes substantial coverage of Servlets and JSP, along with other aspects of enterprise application development.\n\n4. **\"Servlets and JSP: A Tutorial\" by Budi Kurniawan**  \n   This tutorial is well-organized and provides a good mix of theory and hands-on examples. It's suitable for beginners and includes complete project examples.\n\n5. **\"Core Servlets and JavaServer Pages\" by Marty Hall and Larry Brown**  \n   This book dives deep into Servlets and JSP while also providing practical examples. It is updated to include best practices and design patterns.\n\nThese books vary in approach and depth, so you may want to consider your current knowledge level and preferred learning style when selecting one. Happy learning!",
